      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane Property With Outstanding Rates or a Council Notice
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Unpaid council rates, show cause notices, and mandatory rectification orders all affect property sales differently. Here is what sellers need to know before listing.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Brisbane property sales proceed without council complications. But for sellers with outstanding rates balances, unresolved council notices, or mandatory orders attached to the property, the selling process involves additional steps that are worth understanding before you list. The good news is that most council-related issues do not stop a sale from proceeding. The more important question is whether they affect your net proceeds, your disclosure obligations, or your ability to present the property cleanly to buyers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to unpaid council rates at settlement?</h2>
      <p>Unpaid council rates are adjusted at settlement. Your solicitor or conveyancer calculates the outstanding balance and apportions it between the current owner (you, as seller) and the incoming buyer based on the settlement date. The amount owing as at settlement is deducted from the funds released to you, rather than being paid separately or in advance.</p>

      <p>In practical terms, this means that outstanding rates do not prevent a sale from proceeding. They do reduce your net proceeds at settlement. If you are holding a significant rates debt, it is worth knowing the exact figure before you sign a contract, as it affects what you will actually receive. Your solicitor will obtain a rates certificate from Brisbane City Council as part of the settlement preparation, which confirms the balance outstanding and any penalties or interest that have accrued.</p>

      <p>Rates that have been outstanding for an extended period may include interest charges, which accumulate on the overdue balance. Brisbane City Council charges interest on unpaid rates, and for properties with long-standing arrears the interest component can be material. Ask your solicitor to obtain a rates certificate early in the process so you have a clear picture of the total liability before settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Can rates arrears block a property sale?</h2>
      <p>Outstanding rates alone do not prevent a property from being sold. They are a charge on the property that clears at settlement. However, if rates have been unpaid for a very long period and the council has taken legal action to recover the debt, including placing a caveat on the title or commencing rates sale proceedings, the situation becomes more complex. A caveat lodged by the council will appear on the title search and will need to be resolved before settlement can complete.</p>

      <p>Rates sale is an extreme measure that Brisbane City Council rarely uses for residential properties with engaged owners. If your property is at risk of a rates sale action, you will have received multiple formal notices before reaching that point. If you have not engaged with those notices and are now looking to sell, your solicitor will need to contact the council directly to negotiate a resolution as part of the pre-settlement process.</p>

      <p>For most sellers, outstanding rates are a financial consideration rather than a legal obstacle. The rates are simply deducted from your settlement proceeds and the title passes to the buyer unencumbered by the debt.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Types of council notices that affect property sales</h2>
      <p>Council notices attached to a property are a different matter from rates arrears. Where a rates debt is simply a financial obligation that adjusts at settlement, a council notice may impose obligations that attach to the property itself and transfer with ownership. The most relevant types for Brisbane sellers are show cause notices, mandatory rectification orders, and heritage orders.</p>

      <p>A show cause notice is issued when council has identified an alleged breach of planning, building, or environmental legislation and requires the property owner to show cause as to why enforcement action should not be taken. Common triggers include unapproved structures, vegetation management breaches, or land use contraventions. A show cause notice does not automatically prevent a sale, but it is a matter that must be disclosed to buyers under Queensland's seller disclosure obligations. A buyer who discovers an undisclosed show cause notice after signing a contract may have grounds to terminate.</p>

      <p>A mandatory rectification order goes further. Where council has determined that a breach exists and issued an order requiring the owner to carry out specific work, that order binds the property and any subsequent owner. If you sell with an unresolved mandatory rectification order, the buyer inherits the obligation to comply. This must be disclosed in the contract. Whether the buyer accepts this position, or requires you to resolve the order before settlement as a condition of contract, is a negotiation point that affects both the price and the terms of sale.</p>

      <p>Heritage orders and local heritage listings restrict what can be done to a property but do not typically prevent a sale. They are a planning overlay that the buyer takes subject to and should be disclosed in the marketing materials and the contract. Buyers purchasing heritage-listed properties in Brisbane's inner east generally understand the implications, but the obligation to disclose remains.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Seller disclosure obligations for council notices</h2>
      <p>Queensland's seller disclosure framework requires sellers to disclose matters that would affect a reasonable buyer's decision to purchase. A current show cause notice, a mandatory rectification order, or any other council enforcement action on foot at the time of sale falls squarely within this obligation. Disclosure should be made in the contract of sale, typically as a special condition or a notation in the relevant disclosure section, rather than buried in general descriptions or omitted entirely.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor prepares the contract and is responsible for ensuring the disclosure is adequate. If you are aware of any council notices or orders, tell your solicitor before the contract is drafted. Trying to manage or minimise the disclosure is not worth the risk. A buyer who proceeds with full knowledge of a council issue is in a different legal position than one who was not informed, and the consequences of non-disclosure can include contract termination, damages claims, or both.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Resolving council notices before listing</h2>
      <p>Where possible, resolving a council notice before you list avoids complications during the campaign and at the negotiation stage. Buyers who discover an open enforcement action during due diligence tend to use it as a discount lever, often requesting price reductions that exceed the actual cost of resolving the issue. Resolving it in advance removes that leverage and allows the property to be presented cleanly.</p>

      <p>The path to resolving a council notice depends on its nature. For unapproved structures, the typical route is either obtaining retrospective building approval (where the structure meets current standards) or removing the structure. Your solicitor or a town planning consultant can advise on which path is viable for your specific situation. For show cause notices, responding formally to the council and demonstrating that the alleged breach has been remediated, or providing evidence that no breach exists, is the first step.</p>

      <p>If resolution is not practical before listing because of time or cost, the alternative is a transparent disclosure with a price that reflects the buyer's obligation to deal with it. This approach can work, particularly for buyers who have experience with council matters and understand the actual cost of compliance, but it tends to narrow your buyer pool to those with sufficient experience and appetite for that complexity.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The solicitor's role in clearing encumbrances before settlement</h2>
      <p>Your solicitor is responsible for ensuring that all financial obligations and registered encumbrances on the title are resolved at or before settlement. This includes outstanding rates, any mortgage discharge, and any caveats or other registered interests that need to be removed for the buyer to receive clear title.</p>

      <p>For council-related encumbrances, including caveats lodged in relation to rates debts or building enforcement actions, your solicitor will liaise with Brisbane City Council's legal team to negotiate removal. This process takes time and sometimes requires a deed of settlement or payment arrangement. Beginning this process early, well before the expected settlement date, avoids delays that can trigger penalty interest under the contract and frustrate the buyer.</p>

      <p>If you are uncertain about the status of any council matters affecting your property, the best first step is to instruct your solicitor before you list. A title search and a rates certificate will reveal the financial position. A search of Brisbane City Council's records, or a conversation with your town planner if you have had prior dealings with council, will surface any notices or orders that are not yet reflected on the title. Going into a sale process with clear information is always better than discovering issues after you have signed a contract.</p>

